The Redshank is found in considerable numbers in many of the marshes both of Norfolk and Suffolk during the breeding season. It is indeed more common than any other kind of wader. To sportsmen it is very troublesome, fiying around them and uttering an incessant shrill whistle‚ which alarms all the birds near the spot. A few Redshanks are sometimes met with during the winter season‚ but the greater part of them migrate. This species is found solitary and also in fiocks on the ooze of the river Stour.
